{"award_age":73.0,"bio_image":"full\/95102a56f0cc7c7ec892fe2e0bcf7c12057df42a.jpg","category":"Peace","country":"United States","date_of_birth":"1880-12-31T00:00:00.000Z","date_of_death":"1959-10-16T00:00:00.000Z","gender":"male","image_urls":["http:\/\/upload.wikimedia.org\/wikipedia\/commons\/thumb\/9\/91\/General_George_C._Marshall%2C_official_military_photo%2C_1946.JPEG\/250px-General_George_C._Marshall%2C_official_military_photo%2C_1946.JPEG"],"link":"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/George_Marshall","mini_bio":"<p><b>George Catlett Marshall, Jr.<\/b> (December 31, 1880 \u2013 October 16, 1959) was an American soldier and statesman famous for his leadership roles during <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/World_War_II\" title=\"World War II\">World War II<\/a> and the Cold War. He was <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Chief_of_Staff_of_the_United_States_Army\" title=\"Chief of Staff of the United States Army\">Chief of Staff of the United States Army<\/a>, <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/United_States_Secretary_of_State\" title=\"United States Secretary of State\">Secretary of State<\/a>, and the third <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/United_States_Secretary_of_Defense\" title=\"United States Secretary of Defense\">Secretary of Defense<\/a>. He was hailed as the \"organizer of victory\" by <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Winston_Churchill\" title=\"Winston Churchill\">Winston Churchill<\/a> for his leadership of the <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Allies_of_World_War_II\" title=\"Allies of World War II\">Allied<\/a> victory in World War II.<sup id=\"cite_ref-a_4-0\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/George_Marshall#cite_note-a-4\"><span>[<\/span>4<span>]<\/span><\/a><\/sup> Marshall served as the United States Army Chief of Staff during the war and as the chief military adviser to <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/President_of_the_United_States\" title=\"President of the United States\">President<\/a> <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Franklin_D._Roosevelt\" title=\"Franklin D. Roosevelt\">Franklin D. Roosevelt<\/a>.<\/p><p>Marshall's name was given to the <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Marshall_Plan\" title=\"Marshall Plan\">Marshall Plan<\/a>, subsequent to a commencement address he presented as Secretary of State at <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Harvard_University\" title=\"Harvard University\">Harvard University<\/a> in the June of 1947. The speech recommended that the Europeans collectively create their own plan for rebuilding Europe after World War II noting, \"It is logical that the United States should do whatever it is able to do to assist in the return of normal economic health in the world.\" The State Department developed most of the plan, and Truman was shrewd enough to let Marshall's name be attached to it. Unlike Truman, Marshall was widely admired by members of both political parties. Marshall received the <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Nobel_Peace_Prize\" title=\"Nobel Peace Prize\">Nobel Peace Prize<\/a> in 1953 for the plan, which was aimed at the economic recovery of Western Europe after World War II.<sup id=\"cite_ref-b_5-0\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/George_Marshall#cite_note-b-5\"><span>[<\/span>5<span>]<\/span><\/a><\/sup><\/p>","name":"George C. Marshall","place_of_birth":"Uniontown ,  Pennsylvania ,  United States","place_of_death":"Washington, D.C. ,  United States","text":"George C. Marshall , Peace, 1953","year":1953.0}